===Adjective===
{{en-adj|'''more wrong''' or '''[[wronger]]'''|'''most wrong''' or '''[[wrongest]]'''}}

# [[incorrect|Incorrect]] or [[untrue]].
#: ''Some of your answers were correct, and some were '''wrong'''.''
#* '''1592''': [[w:Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]], ''Richard III''; Act II, Scene I, line 54. &mdash; Among this princely heap, if any here By false intelligence or '''wrong''' surmise Hold me a foe...
# [[assert|Asserting]] something [[incorrect]] or [[untrue]].
#: ''You're '''wrong''': he's not Superman at all.''
# [[immoral|Immoral]], not good, [[bad]].
#: ''It is '''wrong''' to lie.''
# [[improper|Improper]]; [[unfit]]; [[unsuitable]].
#: ''A [[bikini]] is the '''wrong''' thing to wear on a cold day.''
# Not working; out of order.
#: ''Something is '''wrong''' with my [[cellphone]]''.
# [[design|Designed]] to be [[worn]] or [[place]]d [[inward]]; as, the '''wrong''' side of a [[garment]] or of a piece of [[cloth]]

====Usage notes====
* {{term||More '''wrong'''}} and {{term||most '''wrong'''}} are preferred in contemporary English. {{term|wronger|Wronger}} and {{term|wrongest}} are currently often used for comedic effect, but were used by Shakespeare in full earnest.

